docs.snippet: BUENOS AIRES, Feb. 5 -- Uruguay, the only South American country that has not had a revolution in a quarter of a century, now presents the spectacle of the President, Dr. Gabriel Terra, leading bitter opposition against the executive branch of the...
docs.lead_paragraph: BUENOS AIRES, Feb. 5 -- Uruguay, the only South American country that has not had a revolution in a quarter of a century, now presents the spectacle of the President, Dr. Gabriel Terra, leading bitter opposition against the executive branch of the government, with the Senate openly charging him with conducting subversive propaganda and the newspapers openly discussing the possibilities of a revolt.
docs.abstract: Pres Terra opposes control of patronage by exec council and urges reform of Constitution

docs.lead_paragraph: BUENOS AIRES, Feb. 6. -- While the ABC-Peru group is exchanging notes to decide on a formula for solution of the Chaco war, with which they expect to show the commission of neutrals in Washington how it should have been done. French and German war methods agraln are struggling for supremacy at the Verdun of the Chaco, as Fort Nanawa has come to be known in South America.

docs.snippet: BUENOS AIRES, Feb. 8 -- Despite its extremely serious probabilities, the Uruguayan situation is taking on many aspects not present in other recent South American internal disputes. It is not the traditional Latin-American conflict between the outs...
docs.lead_paragraph: BUENOS AIRES, Feb. 8 -- Despite its extremely serious probabilities, the Uruguayan situation is taking on many aspects not present in other recent South American internal disputes. It is not the traditional Latin-American conflict between the outs and the ins, but a struggle of one section of the ins to oust other regularly elected ins and quit sharing with them the affairs of government, especially patronage.
